      "prompt": "Your basil is pale and stunting in summer. You cannot afford organic compost yet. Which NPK-laden amendment should you apply directly to the soil, why does it match this specific symptom, and how do you avoid over-salinity?",
      "answer": "Apply a controlled-release fertilizer (like Osmocote) containing balanced N-P-K specifically for tomatoes/ornamentals because nitrogen deficiency causes pale green/yellow leaves. Avoid high-nitrogen lawn food or unmeasured organic manure which may burn roots; test soil pH first to ensure absorption.",
      "rubric": "- Identifies a specific controlled-release granular amendment suitable for heat\n- Correctly links nutrient type (Nitrogen) to the symptom of pale/yellowing leaves",
      "skill": "apply"
    },
    {
      "prompt": "You are mixing top-dressing into your containers. You have 3 lbs bagged slow-release fertilizer labeled '21-0-7' and loose chicken manure known to be high in Nitrogen but lacking Phosphorus. Create a mixture plan: how much of each to use for heavy flowering tomatoes versus leafy herbs, calculating approximate P ratios if you must boost them?",
      "answer": "For leafy herbs needing N-growth only, mix 3 lbs bagged fertilizer (provides all) with no manure; skip the high-N manure as it's excess. For flowering tomatoes boosting blooms, add half a pound of slow-release formula to base soil since the bag has zero P and some manure lacks enough available Phosphorus for flowers.",
      "rubric": "- Distinguishes between nutrient needs for leafy vs. fruiting plants\n- Explains the logical gap in using high-N organic waste without mineral supplement",
      "skill": "produce"
    },
    {
      "prompt": "Your container soil pH is dropping as summer heat rises, causing aluminum toxicity symptoms even with good nutrition. You plan to amend next week's watering cycle. Design a corrective amendment strategy that raises local buffering capacity and protects the root zone from heavy metals.",
      "answer": "Add crushed limestone or dolomitic lime to future waterings; this neutralizes acidity (raises pH) preventing aluminum dissolution which blocks nitrogen uptake, ensuring safe nutrient availability despite rising temperatures affecting soil chemistry.",
      "rubric": "- Proposes a specific alkaline amendment suitable for container irrigation\n- Understands the chemical consequence of low pH on trace metal toxicity",
      "skill": "recall"
    }
  ],
  "note": null,
  "intervention": null
}

